SIMPLE: hypo
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hypo-
<hw>Hy"po-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <?/ under, beneath; akin to L.
<ets>sub</ets>. See <er>Sub-</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A prefix
signifying a <xex>less quantity</xex>, or a <xex>low state</xex> or
<xex>degree</xex>, of that denoted by the word with which it is joined,
or position <xex>under</xex> or <xex>beneath</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A prefix denoting that the
element to the name of which it is prefixed enters with a <xex>low
valence</xex>, or in a <xex>low state of oxidization</xex>, usually the
<xex>lowest</xex>, into the compounds indicated; <as>as,
<ex>hypo</ex>sulphurous acid</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hypo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hypo
<hw>Hy"po</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Hypochondria.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hypo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hypo
<hw>Hy"po</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>hyposulphite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>Sodium
hyposulphite, or thiosulphate, a solution of which is used as a bath to
wash out the unchanged silver salts in a picture.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hypoarian</ent>⟦br⟧
